  .lang.lang-en
    +section('How to visit the Danube Delta?')

      h2 How to visit the Danube Delta?
      p
        | The possibilities to visit the Danube Delta are varied and depend on the time available and the visitors’demands. Access in the Danube Delta is possible through specialized travel agencies, but also by tourists on their own. Tourists who have a limited time available, can take part in one day trip and can choose in this case between trips in large groups (60-80 persons), with modern transport ships, or in smaller groups (6-8 persons), with small ships, the advantage being that these ones can enter into areas inaccessible for the bigger ships. Visitors who want to spend more time in the Danube Delta can also choose between itinerary trips of 6-12 days, on modern and comfortable floating hotels, towed along the authorized routes, and stationary holidays, with accommodation in hotels and pensions from villages or resorts in the Danube Delta.
        | The passionate ones who want to discover themselves the beauty of the delta, can craft their own boat or those of local people that are authorized for tourist activities. In the same way, tourists can travel in the Danube Delta using transportation from authorized shipping companies. It is advisable to rent the services of authorized guides or local people. Tourists’ access in the Danube Delta Biosphere Reserve is based on the access permit issued by the Reserve Authority at its headquarter in Tulcea or in information centres from theritory.
        | Tourists who love angling, should also know that this activity is allowed in the Danube Delta, with a valid sport fishing permit issued by Danube Delta Biosphere Reserve Authority.
